SIMPLE: mendicant
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mendicant
<hw>Men"di*cant</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>mendicans</ets>, <ets>-antis</ets>, p. pr. of <ets>mendicare</ets>
to beg, fr. <ets>mendicus</ets> beggar, indigent.]</ety> <def>Practicing
beggary; begging; living on alms; <as>as, <ex>mendicant</ex>
friars</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mendicant orders</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch.)</fld>,
<cd>certain monastic orders which are forbidden to acquire landed
property and are required to be supported by alms, esp. the Franciscans,
the Dominicans, the Carmelites, and the Augustinians.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendicant</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mendicant
<hw>Men"di*cant</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A beggar; esp., one who makes a
business of begging; specifically, a begging friar.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mendicate</ent>⟦br⟧
